  {
    id:       'strata-a-css-framework-i-actually-wanted',
    readTime: '9 min read',
    category: 'FRAMEWORK',
    title:    'Strata: A CSS Utility Framework I Actually Wanted to Use',
    excerpt:  'Why I built my own utility-class CSS framework instead of reaching for Tailwind or Bootstrap — and what shipping a real site on top of it taught me.',
    date:     'Jul 09, 2026',
    body: [
      'Strata started as an annoyance, not an ambition. I kept reaching for utility-class frameworks and running into the same wall: either the class list ballooned into unreadable noise, or the framework fought me the moment I needed an arbitrary value that wasn’t in its scale. I wanted something that generated only the CSS a project actually used, supported arbitrary values as a first-class citizen — not a bolted-on escape hatch — and stayed out of my way with cascade layers instead of specificity wars.',
      'The core idea is simple: scan the markup for utility-shaped class names, generate exactly those rules, and nothing else. No 400kb reset stylesheet shipped "just in case." This site’s entire utility layer — flex layouts, spacing, color, sizing — is Strata output, and there is no separate CSS framework dependency sitting alongside it. That was the whole point: prove it could carry a real, visually ambitious project, not just a demo page.',
      'Arbitrary values were the feature I cared most about, and also the one that caused the most trouble. `gap-[var(--ex-space-md)]` needs to resolve at build time against whatever token the project defines, including responsive variants like `gap-sm-[...]`. Getting that right — and then getting it right *again* for the responsive prefix cases — took until version 1.4.5 to fully land. Before that it was a documented limitation in this project’s own findings log, worked around with hand-written CSS in the meantime.',
      'Shipping a production site on your own framework is a forcing function no unit test replicates. Building this portfolio surfaced real bugs: a `rounded-pill` layer ordering mismatch, `bg-[...]` resolving to `background-color` when a full `background` shorthand was expected, spacing arbitrary values not replacing underscores correctly. None of these showed up in isolated testing. They showed up because I was using Strata under deadline pressure, the same way any consumer of the library would.',
      'The bugs that stung most were the caching ones — a module-level result cache that could memoize a `null` lookup for a class token that hadn’t appeared in scanned content yet, silently failing to generate CSS for that class on every subsequent build until the dev server restarted. That is not a "write more tests" problem, it is a "dogfood the thing in anger" problem. You do not find a bug like that by testing the framework. You find it by hitting it at 11pm trying to ship a landing page section.',
      'Strata is still evolving, and quickly — between the version that shipped this site’s first pages and the one running today, a whole batch of gaps closed: `grid-template-columns` and `grid-template-rows` got arbitrary support, `font-style` utilities landed, `col-auto` started working. None of that came from a roadmap meeting. It came from hitting the missing piece mid-build and fixing it before moving on. That is the actual development loop: a framework that earns its footprint by generating less, not more, and that gets battle-tested by a real site rather than a synthetic benchmark suite.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Wall', 'The Idea', 'Arbitrary Values', 'Real Bugs Found', 'The Cache Bug', 'Still Evolving'],
  },
  {
    id:       'triforge-a-blender-style-shader-graph-for-three-js',
    readTime: '11 min read',
    category: 'ENGINE',
    title:    'Triforge: A Blender-Style Shader Graph for Three.js',
    excerpt:  'Every planet material on this site compiles from a node graph, not hand-written GLSL. Here is why I built a Blender-workflow shader system for the web, and what it still cannot do.',
    date:     'Jul 09, 2026',
    body: [
      'Every planet surface, atmosphere, and ring in this solar system is defined as a graph of nodes — `PrincipledBSDF`, `ImageTexture`, `Mapping`, `Emission` — the same vocabulary Blender\'s Shading workspace uses. Triforge compiles that graph into a `THREE.ShaderMaterial` at build time. I did not want to hand-write nine planets\' worth of GLSL, and I did not want a black-box material library either. A node graph gives me both: readable material definitions and full control over the compiled output when something needs to be custom.',
      '`@triforge/shader-core` is the center of the suite — a GLSL shader library for Three.js explicitly built around a Blender workflow: texture coordinates flow through mapping and transform nodes into a BSDF, then out through a material output, mirroring the exact graph shape you\'d wire in Blender\'s node editor. `@triforge/keyframe` drives animation on top of it, `@triforge/geometry-nodes` handles procedural scatter (the asteroid belt), and five more packages — `animation-core`, `compositor-core`, `curve-core`, `particle-core`, `modifier-core`, `uv-core`, `volume-core` — are staged for the rest of the suite as this project needs them.',
      'Building a real site on top of an early node-graph library means you find the gaps Blender never has to think about, because Blender does not compile to GLSL for a live WebGL context. `MaterialOutput` originally hardcoded alpha to 1.0 — a graph could not express fresnel- or terminator-driven transparency at all, forcing a project-local `RgbaOutput` escape-hatch node. `ImageTexture.vector` could not accept anything, because every transform node output a vec3 `color` while `vector` sockets are vec2 — the canonical Blender panning graph (`TextureCoordinate → Mapping → ImageTexture`) was simply not expressible, so I wrote a custom `UvPan` node with raw float uniforms instead.',
      'The compiled materials also had no scene-light integration by design — a `ShaderMaterial` only renders what its graph explicitly computes, so a scene `AmbientLight` contributed nothing. Post-conversion, planet night hemispheres that used to get a dim ambient fill under `MeshStandardMaterial` went pitch black under the compiled graph, and Jupiter/Saturn/Uranus/Neptune needed hand-tuned `nightTint` emission constants just to look intentional rather than broken.',
      'I logged every one of these as a numbered finding in the library\'s own `FINDINGS.md`, filed them upstream, and migrated the planetarium forward as each fix published — alpha sockets widened to vec4 in 0.3.0, the vector/color socket conversion and an `ambient` input on `PrincipledBSDF` both landing shortly after. Some are still open: emission-only graphs (every planet atmosphere — fresnel × terminator drives both glow and alpha) still have no alpha path because only `PrincipledBSDF` got one, so `RgbaOutput` cannot be retired yet; and `Mapping`\'s vector parameters aren\'t component-animatable, so the project-local `UvPan` node still exists for the same reason.',
      'I also found and reported a GLSL injection path: `ImageTexture`/`EnvironmentTexture` interpolated a caller-supplied `uniformName` straight into shader source with no validation — same vulnerability class as a patched `Attribute` node, just missed in that sweep. Every current consumer, including this site, hardcodes its uniform names, so it was not exploitable here — but it violated the library\'s own stated rule against interpolating unvalidated strings into GLSL, and it got the same one-line `assertGlslIdentifier` fix once flagged.',
      'None of this makes the library "done" — it makes it real. A shader graph system that only had to survive its own test suite would look cleaner and prove less. This one has nine live materials, a warp transition, and a carousel running on it in production, and every rough edge got sanded down because something on this site actually hit it.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Graph', 'The Suite', 'The Alpha Gap', 'No Ambient Light', 'Fixes Shipped', 'GLSL Injection', 'Still Real'],
  },
  {
    id:       'why-i-built-my-own-tools-instead-of-just-using-what-exists',
    readTime: '8 min read',
    category: 'ORIGIN STORY',
    title:    'Why I Built My Own Tools Instead of Just Using What Exists',
    excerpt:  'Tailwind and Bootstrap exist. Three.js material libraries exist. Here is the actual reasoning behind building Strata and Triforge anyway — not "not invented here," a real gap I kept hitting.',
    date:     'Jul 09, 2026',
    body: [
      'The honest answer to "why did you build your own CSS framework and your own shader system" is not "existing tools are bad." Tailwind is excellent. Three.js material workflows are mature. The honest answer is narrower: I kept hitting the same two specific walls on real projects, and working around them project after project cost more, cumulatively, than building the tool once.',
      'The CSS wall was arbitrary values. Every utility framework treats arbitrary values as an escape hatch bolted onto a fixed scale, not a first-class feature. The moment a project needed `gap-[var(--custom-token)]` with a responsive prefix, I was back to hand-written CSS anyway — which defeats the entire point of a utility layer. Strata\'s whole premise is that arbitrary-value support and scale-based utilities are the same feature, not two tiers of citizenship.',
      'The shader wall was expressiveness versus control. Off-the-shelf Three.js materials (`MeshStandardMaterial`, `MeshPhysicalMaterial`) are a fixed parameter set — you get what the API exposes and nothing else. Hand-written `ShaderMaterial` GLSL is total control but zero structure — every material becomes a bespoke, unmaintainable string of shader code. Triforge exists because I wanted Blender\'s node-graph mental model — composable, inspectable, swappable nodes — compiling down to real GLSL, not a fixed parameter list and not an opaque string.',
      'Building both as real, published npm packages rather than internal project utilities was a deliberate constraint, not a vanity move. An internal helper only has to satisfy the one call site that uses it. A published package has to hold up under a version number, a changelog, and a consumer who does not have the context you have in your head. That discipline is what forces you to actually solve the general problem instead of papering over the specific one in front of you.',
      'It also means every project I build afterward compounds instead of starting over. This portfolio is the first project both tools have had to survive in full production use, at the same time, under a real deadline. Every gap that surfaced here — and there were plenty — is a gap the next project I build will not hit, because it is fixed in the library, not in a one-off workaround buried in this repo.',
      'That is the actual case for building your own tools: not that the existing ones are wrong, but that the compounding return on fixing something at the root, once, in public, under a version number, is worth more over time than fixing it quietly in every project that happens to need it.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Honest Answer', 'The CSS Wall', 'The Shader Wall', 'Why Publish It', 'Compounding Returns', 'The Real Case'],
  },
  {
    id:       'this-site-runs-on-my-own-open-source-work',
    readTime: '7 min read',
    category: 'CASE STUDY',
    title:    'This Site Runs on My Own Open-Source Work',
    excerpt:  'Every surface, every gradient, every planet on this page compiles from Strata and Triforge — my own two public packages. The portfolio is the proof, not the pitch.',
    date:     'Jul 09, 2026',
    body: [
      'It would be easy to write "I built a CSS framework and a shader system" as a bullet point on a resume and move on. This page is the alternative to that bullet point. There is no separate CSS framework loaded here — the entire utility layer, every `d-flex`, every `gap-[...]`, every arbitrary spacing and color value across every planet page, compiles from Strata. There is no material library from npm either — every planet surface, atmosphere, ring, and the warp transition itself compile from Triforge node graphs.',
      'That constraint was deliberate from the start, not a happy accident discovered afterward. Building a portfolio that runs entirely on your own tools means you cannot quietly patch around a limitation with a competing library when you hit one — you either fix the tool or you ship something broken. That pressure is exactly why both packages moved as fast as they did during this build: `strata-css` went through multiple patch versions closing arbitrary-value and layer-ordering gaps mid-project, and `@triforge/shader-core` went through a documented sequence of alpha-socket, ambient-lighting, and UV-transform fixes for the same reason.',
      'The Three.js foundation under Triforge deserves its own mention: this is not a from-scratch renderer, it is a purpose-built node-graph compiler sitting on top of Three.js, targeting the exact Blender-workflow mental model — texture coordinate, mapping, BSDF, material output — used to define all nine planet materials plus the warp starfield and the carousel\'s eight mini-renderers. Astro 6 hosts it all as a true MPA: every planet is its own route, the warp transition is the connective tissue between them, and the 3D scene only boots on the pages that need it.',
      'The proof this arrangement offers a recruiter or a technical reviewer is different from a code sample. A code sample shows you can write a function. A site that visibly runs on two of your own published packages, with real version history and a real findings log of bugs found and fixed under production pressure, shows you can own a piece of infrastructure long enough for it to mature — and that you\'ll fix the actual root cause instead of quietly working around it in the one place it happened to bite.',
      'It is also, practically, a live demo that updates itself. Every time Strata or Triforge ships a fix, this site is running it in production the next time it deploys. There is no separate "demo project" that goes stale while the real work happens elsewhere. The demo and the work are the same repository.',
    ],
    topics: ['No Separate Framework', 'Deliberate Constraint', 'Astro + Triforge', 'The Real Proof', 'A Living Demo'],
  },
  {
    id:       'the-ghost-planet-bug',
    readTime: '9 min read',
    category: 'POSTMORTEM',
    title:    'The Ghost Planet Bug: When Nine Planets Went Untextured Overnight',
    excerpt:  'A shader-core version bump silently broke fragment compilation on every planet surface, with zero console errors. Here is how it was found and fixed.',
    date:     'Jul 09, 2026',
    body: [
      'The symptom was blunt: after bumping `@triforge/shader-core`, every planet in the solar system scene rendered untextured — flat, ghostly spheres with no surface detail. No console error. No thrown exception. No red text anywhere. The build passed. The dev server ran clean. The planets were just gone, silently, which is the worst kind of bug because there is no stack trace pointing at the cause.',
      'The root cause was a socket contract change between versions: `MaterialOutput.surface` had started requiring a vec4 shader socket, where the previous version accepted vec3. Every one of the eight planet surface graphs in this project fed it a vec3 `Gamma` color output — valid under the old contract, silently invalid under the new one. The fragment shader was failing to compile, and because the failure happened inside a compiled `ShaderMaterial`\'s GLSL, not inside JavaScript, nothing in the normal dev console surfaced it as an application error.',
      'Finding it meant stepping outside the usual debugging loop. Console errors, breakpoints, and React/Astro devtools are all built around JavaScript exceptions — this failure lived entirely inside GPU shader compilation, a layer those tools do not instrument by default. The actual signal was buried in the WebGL context\'s shader-compile log, which only surfaces if you go looking for it specifically, and the fix required tracing the exact socket type expectations through the new version\'s `MaterialOutput` node rather than guessing from the visual symptom alone.',
      'The fix was small once located: wrap every planet\'s final color through an `Emission` pass-through node before it reaches `MaterialOutput`, producing a valid vec4 instead of the raw vec3. Same visual output, correct socket type. While in there, I also caught and fixed a second, unrelated problem the same investigation surfaced: several planets had hardcoded per-planet night-tint emission constants that had been tuned back when the scene still had ambient light reaching night hemispheres — with that ambient path since removed, the night sides were reading as dim colored fog instead of true black. Zeroed the default ambient strength and let night hemispheres render correctly dark.',
      'The lesson that stuck: a version bump on a library with a compiled-shader boundary needs a visual regression pass, not just "the build passed and no errors printed." Silent GPU-side failures do not announce themselves in any of the places developers are trained to look first. Since this incident, every triforge upgrade on this project gets an explicit before/after screenshot comparison across all nine planets before it ships — a rule that exists specifically because this bug got as far as it did before anyone noticed the surfaces were gone.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Symptom', 'The Root Cause', 'Finding It', 'The Fix', 'The Lesson'],
  },
  {
    id:       'building-the-warp-router',
    readTime: '8 min read',
    category: 'ARCHITECTURE',
    title:    'Building the Warp Router: A Site-Wide Page Transition in a Multi-Page App',
    excerpt:  'Every click on this site plays a fullscreen GLSL warp-speed effect before the page actually navigates. Here is how that works inside a real MPA, not an SPA.',
    date:     'Jul 09, 2026',
    body: [
      'This site is a true multi-page app — Astro 6, every planet its own route, full page loads between them, no client-side router. Getting a fullscreen warp-speed transition to play consistently across that architecture, on every single link click, is a different problem than it would be in an SPA where a router already owns the navigation lifecycle. `WarpRouter` has to own both halves of every navigation itself: what happens the instant before the page unloads, and what happens the instant after the next page\'s first paint.',
      'The forward half intercepts every internal `<a href>` click site-wide with a single capturing click listener, filters out anything that should not be warped — new-tab, download, modifier-key clicks, external URLs, `mailto:`/`tel:` links, anchors — and for everything else calls `preventDefault`, sets the warp\'s glow color to match the destination page, fades a fullscreen veil in, plays the forward warp animation, and only then sets `window.location.href` in the animation\'s completion callback. The destination color comes from a `PAGE_COLORS` map keyed by route, and — because this same router also has to cover Mercury\'s `/sol?target=mercury` deep-link pattern — it resolves `?target=` query params against that same map before falling back to the path itself.',
      'The reverse half is the harder problem, because a fresh page load has no "previous page" context to animate out of — it has to fake continuity from a cold start. Every page calls `WarpRouter.init()` on load, which immediately plays a reverse warp using the current page\'s own color and holds a fullscreen veil opaque for a short, deliberately named `WARP_VEIL_HOLD_MS` (220ms) before fading it out — giving the 3D scene one full frame to actually finish initializing before it is revealed, rather than exposing whatever half-loaded state exists the instant the script runs.',
      'The bfcache case is what actually broke first in practice. Back/forward navigation in a browser does not reload the page — it restores a frozen DOM snapshot from the browser\'s cache, and that snapshot can include whatever transient veil state was on screen when the page was suspended. Without explicit handling, a restored page would flash its frozen, veil-transparent state before any script had a chance to re-cover it. The fix runs on two events: `pagehide` synchronously forces the veil to a fully-opaque `instant-on` state right before the page is frozen into cache, guaranteeing whatever gets snapshotted is already covered; `pageshow` with `event.persisted === true` re-triggers the full reverse-warp entry sequence exactly as if it were a fresh load.',
      'One structural decision paid for itself repeatedly: the veil\'s state lives entirely in a single `data-veilState` attribute (`instant-on` / `fading-in` / `fading-out` / `hidden`), driven purely by CSS transitions, with the terminal `hidden` state only ever set from a real `transitionend` event rather than a fixed timeout. That closed a subtle bug where the veil could rest indefinitely on the transient `fading-out` name if a transition got interrupted — the state machine now always settles on a name that accurately describes what is on screen, verified with headless Chromium sampling `getComputedStyle` at the exact moment of navigation commit.',
    ],
    topics: ['The MPA Problem', 'The Forward Half', 'The Reverse Half', 'The bfcache Case', 'One Clean State'],
  },
  {
    id:       'maintaining-packages-i-depend-on',
    readTime: '9 min read',
    category: 'MAINTENANCE',
    title:    'Maintaining Packages I Depend On',
    excerpt:  'Shipping a real product on top of your own early-stage npm packages turns every bug your users would hit into a bug you hit first, at the worst possible time.',
    date:     'Jul 09, 2026',
    body: [
      'There is a specific kind of pressure that only shows up when you are both the maintainer and the first real consumer of a library. A bug filed by an external user is a report you can schedule around. A bug you hit yourself, at 11pm, three sections into building a page that is due tomorrow, is a bug you have to actually understand and fix before you can keep moving. Building this portfolio on Strata and Triforge — both still early-stage, both under active development — put me in that position constantly, and it changed how I think about maintaining open-source software.',
      'The clearest example is a security-class finding I caught in Triforge\'s own shader-core package: `ImageTexture` and `EnvironmentTexture` both interpolated a caller-supplied `uniformName` string directly into generated GLSL source, with no validation — the exact same vulnerability class an earlier patch had already fixed on a different node (`Attribute`), just missed in that original sweep. A hostile `uniformName` value could inject arbitrary GLSL into the compiled shader. Every current consumer of the library, including this site, hardcodes its uniform names, so it was not actually exploitable in production here — but finding it meant auditing every place a string reaches generated shader source, not just the one place a previous patch had already touched, and applying the same `assertGlslIdentifier` guard consistently rather than trusting that one fix meant the whole surface was covered.',
      'A second real bug came from a subtler place: a stale in-memory cache. Strata\'s CSS generator holds a module-level result cache for the lifetime of the dev process — if an arbitrary utility class was looked up once before it existed in scanned content, the cache would memoize a `null` result for that exact class token, and every subsequent build would return that cached `null` immediately, silently, without ever re-running the actual pattern match that would now succeed. The class simply never generated CSS again until the dev server restarted. That is not a bug a unit test catches, because a unit test does not simulate a developer typing a class name into a file before saving it. It is a bug you only find by actually building something under real editing conditions.',
      'The upstream discipline that made both of these fixable rather than just workaround-able was keeping a running, dated findings log — not a vague "known issues" note, but a numbered list with reproduction steps, root cause analysis, the specific file and line, and a status (open / partially resolved / resolved-and-verified-on-the-published-version, not just resolved-in-the-monorepo). Several Triforge findings went through exactly that lifecycle: reported, fixed in the monorepo, and only marked resolved here after being re-verified against the actual published npm version — because a fix that exists in a git branch but has not shipped yet is not a fix a consumer can rely on.',
      'The uncomfortable but useful realization is that shipping a real product on your own infrastructure removes your ability to be vague with yourself about whether something is "basically done." Either the graph compiles clean across all nine planets and `astro build` passes, or it does not. Either the arbitrary CSS class generates on save, or it silently doesn\'t. Maintaining tools this way — under the same deadline pressure any other consumer would feel — is a slower way to hit 1.0, but it is the only way I have found to actually trust that a fix works, rather than hoping it does.',
    ],
    topics: ['Maintainer Pressure', 'The Security Bug', 'The Cache Bug', 'The Findings Log', 'The Realization'],
  },
];
